RUCHI BEZOLES: Yeah.

00:06:48.750 --> 00:06:50.670
BEN GREENWOOD: So using
these smart filters

00:06:50.670 --> 00:06:52.140
is a really powerful
way that you

00:06:52.140 --> 00:06:53.760
can make it easier
for your users

00:06:53.760 --> 00:06:57.180
to find just the content
they're looking for.

00:06:57.180 --> 00:06:59.500
And I'm going to show
you a few code examples.

00:06:59.500 --> 00:07:02.310
And as the library
API is a RESTful API,

00:07:02.310 --> 00:07:05.370
you can play along whether you
are a mobile, back end, or web

00:07:05.370 --> 00:07:08.070
developer.

00:07:08.070 --> 00:07:10.560
The first category--
or the first filter,

00:07:10.560 --> 00:07:12.750
excuse me, that we
were most excited about

00:07:12.750 --> 00:07:14.310
are content categories.

00:07:14.310 --> 00:07:16.950
And as Ruchi mentioned, these
use Google's computer vision

00:07:16.950 --> 00:07:19.140
to figure out what
an image is about

00:07:19.140 --> 00:07:23.280
so you can filter and narrow
down results in your app.

00:07:23.280 --> 00:07:26.130
The API offers many
categories to choose from.

00:07:26.130 --> 00:07:28.480
And as you can see
from this example,

00:07:28.480 --> 00:07:31.020
I can also exclude
categories that might not

00:07:31.020 --> 00:07:33.630
make sense for my use case.

00:07:33.630 --> 00:07:35.730
For example, an
app like Timehop,

00:07:35.730 --> 00:07:39.310
which is there to really remind
me of my fondest memories,

00:07:39.310 --> 00:07:42.990
may not want to include pictures
of old bills and receipts

00:07:42.990 --> 00:07:45.420
and other documents
from years ago.

00:07:45.420 --> 00:07:46.950
And filters are
a great way to be

00:07:46.950 --> 00:07:50.770
able to exclude this content.

00:07:50.770 --> 00:07:55.170
Another way that users explore
their content is based on time.

00:07:55.170 --> 00:07:58.110
And sometimes, you'll want to
present photos chronologically

00:07:58.110 --> 00:08:00.270
so you can scroll back in time.

00:08:00.270 --> 00:08:01.860
But there are other
use cases where

00:08:01.860 --> 00:08:04.050
being able to just jump
to the right moment

00:08:04.050 --> 00:08:08.800
can make it much easier for your
users to find their content.

00:08:08.800 --> 00:08:12.390
As you can see, you can filter
by specific dates or date

00:08:12.390 --> 00:08:16.140
ranges, and you can also
combine filters together

00:08:16.140 --> 00:08:18.730
to be even more expressive.

00:08:18.730 --> 00:08:22.680
Say I wanted to find all of my
birthday photos from years past

00:08:22.680 --> 00:08:24.900
and put them together
in a collage.

00:08:24.900 --> 00:08:27.930
I could sit there and scroll
through decades of photos

00:08:27.930 --> 00:08:30.420
to try and find
just the right pics,

00:08:30.420 --> 00:08:34.020
or I could combine a
date and content category

00:08:34.020 --> 00:08:37.169
filter like this.

00:08:37.169 --> 00:08:40.419
You can see how we've
emitted the year here

00:08:40.419 --> 00:08:42.240
and left it as a
wildcard so it'll

00:08:42.240 --> 00:08:47.580
match any days on my birthday
and included a content category

00:08:47.580 --> 00:08:50.580
filter to find those
great selfies and birthday

00:08:50.580 --> 00:08:52.310
celebration moments.

00:08:52.310 --> 00:08:55.080
It's pretty neat.

00:08:55.080 --> 00:08:58.380
Of course, you can also
filter by other kinds

00:08:58.380 --> 00:09:01.390
of media types,
so photos, videos,

00:09:01.390 --> 00:09:04.410
or other kinds of
content, like VR.

00:09:04.410 --> 00:09:07.380
And you can select photos
that are already in an album

00:09:07.380 --> 00:09:11.610
that a user has curated
for some purpose.

00:09:11.610 --> 00:09:14.160
But regardless of
the filters you use,

00:09:14.160 --> 00:09:17.890
you'll get back a list of what
we refer to as media items.

00:09:17.890 --> 00:09:20.850
And here's what one looks like.

00:09:20.850 --> 00:09:24.240
Google Photos supports a wide
variety of media formats,

00:09:24.240 --> 00:09:27.450
from the obvious photos
and videos to animations

00:09:27.450 --> 00:09:31.960
and even complex VR
and 360 degree images.

00:09:31.960 --> 00:09:35.740
So for each media item, you'll
get back this consistent JSON

00:09:35.740 --> 00:09:37.170
object.

00:09:37.170 --> 00:09:40.960
And there are a couple of
interesting attributes here.

00:09:40.960 --> 00:09:42.750
The first is the
base URL, and this

00:09:42.750 --> 00:09:45.330
is what your application
uses to access

00:09:45.330 --> 00:09:49.650
the image bytes themselves so
you can show them in your app.

00:09:49.650 --> 00:09:53.340
A subtle but really
powerful feature of this URL

00:09:53.340 --> 00:09:55.700
is that it has
built-in resizing.

00:09:55.700 --> 00:09:57.630
So with a simple
parameter, you can

00:09:57.630 --> 00:10:01.140
ask Google Photos to return an
image that fits the dimensions

00:10:01.140 --> 00:10:03.930
or aspect ratio for
your device, saving you

00:10:03.930 --> 00:10:06.700
a lot of boilerplate code.

00:10:06.700 --> 00:10:08.850
It also makes it really
easy to reduce data

00:10:08.850 --> 00:10:10.680
transfer for users on mobile.

00:10:13.220 --> 00:10:16.080
The second URL here
is a product URL.

00:10:16.080 --> 00:10:20.130
And what this is is a deep
link back into Google Photos.

00:10:20.130 --> 00:10:21.690
This can be really
helpful if you

00:10:21.690 --> 00:10:25.110
want to provide a complete
and comprehensive UX

00:10:25.110 --> 00:10:29.640
with common tasks like cropping,
rotating, and even viewing

00:10:29.640 --> 00:10:32.520
complicated formats, such as VR.

00:10:32.520 --> 00:10:34.800
You can just link
out to Google Photos

00:10:34.800 --> 00:10:37.770
rather than rebuilding all
of that code in your own app.

00:10:40.990 --> 00:10:43.000
And then, of course,
there's other metadata,

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:46.450
depending on the media
format you're dealing with.

00:10:46.450 --> 00:10:48.400
And what's powerful
about this is

00:10:48.400 --> 00:10:51.640
Google Photos will extract
this from a variety of media

00:10:51.640 --> 00:10:55.180
formats, so you don't have to go
through and parse it yourself.

00:10:55.180 --> 00:11:00.880
You'll have it returned in
this consistent JSON object.

00:11:00.880 --> 00:11:03.110
And so with all of
this data together,

00:11:03.110 --> 00:11:05.890
you're able to build and
include the user's content

00:11:05.890 --> 00:11:09.880
inside of your user experience
and make it seamless and fast

00:11:09.880 --> 00:11:13.540
for them to bring photos and
videos into your application,

00:11:13.540 --> 00:11:16.581
just like the examples
we showed earlier.

