00:15:13.350 --> 00:15:18.300
And now, we're going to try and
save it all in Google Photos.

00:15:18.300 --> 00:15:19.970
So the first thing
we'll do with the API

00:15:19.970 --> 00:15:22.560
is go ahead and create an album.

00:15:22.560 --> 00:15:24.840
Simply send a POST request--

00:15:24.840 --> 00:15:29.550
excuse me-- and you can
specify the title of the album.

00:15:29.550 --> 00:15:31.080
And in the response,
you'll get back

00:15:31.080 --> 00:15:33.990
an ID, which we'll
use in just a second,

00:15:33.990 --> 00:15:36.270
and a product URL,
which is, again,

00:15:36.270 --> 00:15:40.740
a deep link so you can show
the content in Google Photos.

00:15:40.740 --> 00:15:43.420
As you can see, the
album's empty for now.

00:15:43.420 --> 00:15:44.170
So let's fix that.

00:15:46.830 --> 00:15:49.740
Second step is to
upload the actual image

00:15:49.740 --> 00:15:51.990
bytes to Google servers.

00:15:51.990 --> 00:15:55.200
Because we support a wide
variety of media formats,

00:15:55.200 --> 00:15:57.870
you typically won't need
to worry about transcoding

00:15:57.870 --> 00:15:59.250
between formats.

00:15:59.250 --> 00:16:02.130
You just upload the bytes, and
the service will give you back

00:16:02.130 --> 00:16:04.680
an upload token.

00:16:04.680 --> 00:16:08.490
And we'll use it here in
the Create Media Item call,

00:16:08.490 --> 00:16:10.950
as you can see.

00:16:10.950 --> 00:16:14.677
We'll also fill in the album
ID that we just created.

00:16:14.677 --> 00:16:17.010
And at this point, you're
probably thinking, OK, thanks,

00:16:17.010 --> 00:16:17.610
Ben.

00:16:17.610 --> 00:16:19.820
We've talked a lot,
done a lot of plumbing,

00:16:19.820 --> 00:16:21.030
moved some IDs around.

00:16:21.030 --> 00:16:23.580
How about you show me
something interesting?

00:16:23.580 --> 00:16:26.670
Well, a big benefit of Google
Photos is being able to search

00:16:26.670 --> 00:16:28.980
by what you remember.

00:16:28.980 --> 00:16:31.110
Some of this happens
automatically, thanks to AI.

00:16:31.110 --> 00:16:34.140
So I could search
for the Eiffel Tower

00:16:34.140 --> 00:16:37.020
and find pictures I've
taken of the Eiffel Tower.

00:16:37.020 --> 00:16:41.820
But there are some things that
only you or your app knows.

00:16:41.820 --> 00:16:44.340
In this case, I'm taking
a photo of an area

00:16:44.340 --> 00:16:47.250
my friends told me to go and
look at called "the pound."

00:16:47.250 --> 00:16:48.210
And it's colloquial.

00:16:48.210 --> 00:16:51.450
It's not on the maps,
so only I remember it.

00:16:51.450 --> 00:16:53.490
But I can put it
in the description

00:16:53.490 --> 00:16:55.500
with a few extra
details, and you'll

00:16:55.500 --> 00:16:58.680
see that this, then, becomes
searchable in Google Photos.

00:16:58.680 --> 00:17:01.900
And all that context is
stored right with the image,

00:17:01.900 --> 00:17:04.839
so I can see it again
in years to come.

00:17:04.839 --> 00:17:07.020
This is a great tool you
can use in your apps.

00:17:07.020 --> 00:17:08.790
Maybe you're building
a game, and you

00:17:08.790 --> 00:17:11.520
want players to be able to
save their favorite moments

00:17:11.520 --> 00:17:15.150
and include the player's
name or the level

00:17:15.150 --> 00:17:17.270
that their character was at.

00:17:17.270 --> 00:17:20.229
Or maybe you're just delivering
marathon finish line photos

00:17:20.229 --> 00:17:22.770
and want to be able to remind
the user of the great time they

00:17:22.770 --> 00:17:24.510
got.

00:17:24.510 --> 00:17:26.339
But let's be honest,
individual photos

00:17:26.339 --> 00:17:28.920
aren't all that
interesting on their own.

00:17:28.920 --> 00:17:33.984
So through the power of this
clicker, we'll add a few more.

00:17:33.984 --> 00:17:35.400
Now, we mentioned
earlier that you

00:17:35.400 --> 00:17:37.800
can create rich
albums that contain

00:17:37.800 --> 00:17:41.820
text headings, locations, maps,
and even control the album

00:17:41.820 --> 00:17:42.762
layout.

00:17:42.762 --> 00:17:44.220
And in Google
Photos, we call these

00:17:44.220 --> 00:17:47.820
features album enrichments.

00:17:47.820 --> 00:17:50.490
Because there's not a whole
lot else to do in the desert,

00:17:50.490 --> 00:17:53.190
each day I took a few
notes about the track.

00:17:53.190 --> 00:17:55.020
And now, using
album enrichments,

00:17:55.020 --> 00:17:59.820
I can group together my photos
to tell a meaningful story.

00:17:59.820 --> 00:18:03.600
To do this, we'll go ahead
and call Add Enrichment

00:18:03.600 --> 00:18:08.340
and create a text enrichment.

00:18:08.340 --> 00:18:11.390
And finally, specifying the
position for the enrichment

00:18:11.390 --> 00:18:14.780
to be displayed in the album,
maybe after the last photo

00:18:14.780 --> 00:18:15.570
I took each day.

00:18:18.470 --> 00:18:21.460
And as you can see, this
creates headings and dividers,

00:18:21.460 --> 00:18:25.080
and our album's really
starting to come together now.

00:18:25.080 --> 00:18:29.000
There are other kinds of
enrichments you can add, too.

00:18:29.000 --> 00:18:31.410
I could add individual
locations or even

00:18:31.410 --> 00:18:34.020
maps that describe the journey.

00:18:34.020 --> 00:18:36.990
And this can be useful for
all sorts of applications.

00:18:36.990 --> 00:18:38.850
Maybe you're an
amusement park, and you

00:18:38.850 --> 00:18:41.220
want to be able to deliver
photos from the rides

00:18:41.220 --> 00:18:44.330
that someone's just
taken in the park.

00:18:44.330 --> 00:18:46.020
Or maybe you're just
trying to document

00:18:46.020 --> 00:18:49.410
the progress of a project,
like building your first home

00:18:49.410 --> 00:18:52.110
or seeing your child's
art project progress

00:18:52.110 --> 00:18:54.660
throughout the school term.

00:18:54.660 --> 00:18:57.360
But for my hiking app,
